{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing — missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS/MOCK-HIDE: a unit test of only the validator can miss orchestration bugs where downstream insurance/triage/scheduling still runs. Minimum failure boundary is request handler + validator + pipeline gate wiring.","test_description":"Run intake submission through the real intake service layer with missing `name` and `insurance_id`; assert response contains both missing fields in one error and assert no downstream steps were invoked (no insurance call, no triage request, no scheduling write).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"REAL-INFRA: none. This is deterministic date parsing/range logic in one boundary; pure function tests catch real failures directly.","test_description":"Test DOB validator function with cases: tomorrow’s date, date older than 150 years, malformed strings, and valid boundary dates; assert exact error categories for each invalid input.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The insurance eligibility check sends the correct patient ID and plan code to the payer API and correctly interprets the \"eligible\" vs \"not eligible\" vs \"pending\" response.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: request-shape and status-mapping bugs often appear only against real HTTP contract (auth headers, serialization, status/body nuances). Pure mocks can falsely pass.","test_description":"Call the insurance client against the payer sandbox (or a real contract endpoint) for controlled test patients; verify outbound payload contains exact patient ID/plan code and verify system maps returned states to internal `eligible`, `not_eligible`, `pending`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the payer API is unreachable, the system marks eligibility as \"pending\" and continues the intake rather than blocking.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: unreachable behavior depends on real timeout/network failure semantics. MOCK-HIDE: mocked exceptions may not match production timeout/retry behavior.","test_description":"Run intake with payer endpoint intentionally unreachable (e.g., blackholed host or refused connection) and production timeout settings; assert eligibility is persisted as `pending`, pipeline proceeds to triage/scheduling, and no hard failure is returned.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The AI symptom triage correctly assigns high urgency to symptom combinations that indicate emergency conditions (e.g., chest pain + shortness of breath).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: correctness depends on real model reasoning/classification quality and may vary run-to-run. Non-agentic mocks cannot validate true triage quality.","test_description":"Send emergency symptom scenarios to the real medical reasoning model across repeated trials; require high-urgency classification rate above threshold and flag regressions in model output quality.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The symptom triage produces a natural language explanation of its urgency assessment that a clinician can review, not just a numeric score.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: explanation existence and clinical readability depend on generated model output, not just field plumbing. Mocks can hide empty/low-quality explanations.","test_description":"Invoke real triage model with representative symptoms; assert output includes non-empty clinician-facing explanation text with rationale elements (symptoms cited + urgency reasoning), not only a score/code.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"An appointment is scheduled in the first available slot that matches the assigned urgency level — high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within 48 hours.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: depends on scheduler logic + shared calendar DB query/write ordering. Unit tests of slot-selection alone can miss data-access and boundary-time bugs.","test_description":"With a seeded calendar DB, run scheduling service for high and medium urgency referrals; assert chosen slot is earliest valid one and satisfies SLA windows (same-day for high, <=48h for medium).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The scheduling step does not double-book a time slot even when two patients are being processed concurrently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: race conditions are hidden by single-threaded mocks; need real DB constraints/transactions with concurrent execution at module+DB boundary.","test_description":"Fire two concurrent scheduling requests targeting the same scarce slot against a real test calendar DB with